definition.value: An organic anionic group that is ferriheme c(1-) bound to cytochrome c by two L-cysteine residues; major species at pH 7.3.

belongs to the class of organic compounds known as dipeptides. TMAP was previously an unknown potential plasma biomarker for glomerular filtration rate (GFR) but its structure has since been elucidated (PMID: 28706470 ). TMAP has also been identified as a potential plasma biomarker of reduced kidney function in early chronic kidney disease (CKD), end stage renal disease (ESRD), and hemodialytic clearance (PMID: 31048706 )
A mogroside that is mogrol in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 24 has been replaced by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of protons from the carboxy groups to the amino groups of Asp-Lys; major species at pH 7.3.
A peptide cation obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy terminus and protonation of the amino groups of Lys-Ala; major species at pH 7.3.
A peptide cation obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy terminus and protonation of the amino groups of Arg-Gly; major species at pH 7.3.
A peptide cation obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy terminus and protonation of the amino groups of Lys-Lys; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of His-Gly; major species at pH 7.3.

A member of the class of quinolines that is quinoline substituted by a 6-[4-(piperazin-1-yl)phenyl]pyrazolo[1,5-a]pyrimidin-3-yl group at position 5. It is a potent ALK inhibitor (IC50 values of 2.4, 1.3, 85.8, 2,133 and 9,276 nM for ALK1, ALK2, ALK3, ALK4 and ALK5, respectively).

A pyrazolopyrimidine that is pyrazolo[1,5-a]pyrimidine substituted by phenyl and 4-[2-(morpholin-4-yl)ethoxy]phenyl groups at positions 3 and 6, respectively. It is an inhibitor of VEGFR-2 (IC50 = 0.16 muM).
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of any L-histidyl-L-alpha-amino acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide cation that is the conjugate acid of any L-lysyl-L-alpha-amino acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide cation that is the conjugate acid of any L-aminoacyl-L-lysine; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of any L-aminoacyl-L-histidine; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide cation that is the conjugate acid of any L-aminoacyl-L-arginine; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of protons from the carboxy groups to the amino groups of Lys-Asp; major species at pH 7.3.

A member of the class of aminoquinolines that is is quinoline substituted by 5-methylfuran-2-yl, (1-methylpiperidin-4-yl)amino, methoxy, and 3-(pyrrolidin-1-yl)propoxy groups at positions 2, 4, 6 and 7, respectively. It is a dual G9a/DNA methyltransferases inhibitor with antitumor activity. It inhibits G9a, DNMT1, DNMT3A, DNMT3B and GLP (IC50 = 8 nM, 382 nM, 85 nM, 1200 nM and 2 nM, respectively).

A member of the class of carbazoles that is 1,3-di(9H-carbazol-9-yl)propan-2-ol in which the hydroxy group is replaced by a 2-hydroxy-3-[(propan-2-yl)amino]propoxy group. It is a DNA methyltransferase 1 inhibitor (IC50 = 1.7 muM).

An organosulfate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of cyclosporin A hydrogen sulfate resulting from the deprotonation of the sulfooxy group. It is a metabolite of cyclosporin A found in human bile and plasma.
A berberine alkaloid that is 5,8,13,13a-tetrahydro-6H-[1,3]dioxolo[4,5-g]isoquino[3,2-a]isoquinoline substituted by methoxy groups at positions 9 and 10.
